Serious but fixable, the mayor concluded. It's scarcely a late summer breeze. This is the eye of the hurricane. Bricks, sticks and leaves littered the street. Phone and electric service to the city command post was knocked out. Late in the day, there was hope Hugo might spare Charleston. Riley, city officials and a few reporters stayed in Charleston's historic City Hall through Thursday night as the area's worst hurricane in three decades pounded the coastal city where the Civil War began.  watched the fury it vented on his beloved, 300-year-old city.  Riley Jr. 